  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Wandering Mount Jiri
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mount Duryu rises deep as evening clouds descend so low,
    Ten thousand valleys, thousand crags—like會계's peaks they show.
    I lean upon my staff to seek the Grotto of the Azure Crane,
    But hear instead across the woods the white gibbon's refrain.

    Towers shimmer distantly while the Three Isles fade from sight,
    Moss-covered characters still gleam with that ancient light.
    I ask where lies the Peach Blossom Spring, that realm supreme—
    Yet falling flowers drift downstream, dissolving all my dream.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Duryu (頭流山) is an alternative name for Mount Jiri, one of Korea's sacred mountains.
  - key: ''
    value: Mount會계 refers to Mount Kuaiji in China, famous for its profound valleys and peaks, evoked here as a comparison.
  - key: ''
    value: The Grotto of the Azure Crane (靑鶴洞) is a legendary sacred site said to exist within Mount Jiri.
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Isles (三山) alludes to the mythical islands of the immortals in Chinese Daoist tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The Peach Blossom Spring (桃源) references Tao Yuanming's famous allegory of an earthly paradise, suggesting the poet's quest for an idealized realm beyond the material world.
